---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import '../styles/pages/about.css';
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="Laurie Di Francesco — artist-author working through photography and writing."
>

  <!-- ── Titre + Épigraphe ────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="about-head container">
    <p class="about-eyebrow">About</p>
    <h1 class="about-h1">Laurie Di Francesco</h1>

    <div class="about-epi">
      <blockquote>
        All men by nature desire to know. An indication of this is the delight we
        take in our senses; for even apart from their usefulness they are loved for
        themselves; and above all others <span class="k">the sense of sight</span>.
      </blockquote>
      <cite>Aristotle — Metaphysics, Book A</cite>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Bio ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="about-bio">

    <div class="bio-portrait">
      <img
        src="/images/about-redscarf-softened.jpg"
        alt="Laurie Di Francesco"
        loading="eager"
      />
    </div>

    <p>Laurie Di Francesco is an artist-author working primarily through photography and writing.</p>

    <p>She grew up between France and Italy. This dual belonging made her grasp, very early,
    <span class="k">the strength and the fragility of the threshold</span>, and question what
    it means to be rooted — here or there, elsewhere or nowhere; a displacement that reaches
    even the language in which she thinks.</p>

    <p><span class="k">The blue of the sky</span>, unchanging on either side of the earth,
    is a recurring motif in her work — one she questions as a possible anchor to the world.</p>

    <p>The camera — disposables at first, then a point-and-shoot received as a child — became,
    very early, her way of documenting and linking her two shores. Her work rests on
    <span class="k">a certain power of gentleness</span>, a counterpoint to the difficulty of
    inhabiting several places at once and of giving new meaning to the fractures we all carry
    within. In <em>Toward the Blue</em> or <em>En corps à la mer</em>, this gentleness extends
    into a dreamlike quality close to <span class="k">magical realism</span>: the real lets
    itself be crossed by dream without ever quite dissolving into it.</p>

    <p>As a young adult she moved to <span class="k">Brazil</span> — a land of the heart, and
    of expansion for her practice; she took her first photography classes at twenty, in Rio de
    Janeiro, at the Ateliê da Imagem. More recently she refined her technique and her art of
    storytelling at the ENSP in Arles, then alongside professionals such as Fabienne Pavia,
    Antoine d'Agata and Klavdij Sluban.</p>

    <p>A graduate in philosophy, she approaches art as an <span class="k">existentialist</span>:
    Nietzsche for perspectivism — not as relativism, but as the demand to multiply points of
    view; Ricœur for otherness and freedom; Bachelard for the gratuitous beauty of forms. So
    many ways of thinking what she already practices with a camera: to transfigure the real
    without idealizing it, in what it holds of light as much as of fragility.</p>

    <p>She exhibited for the first time in Belo Horizonte, Brazil, in 2024 —
    <em>Déborder les lignes (Spilling Beyond the Lines)</em>, built from archival images.</p>

    <p>Her work continues today across several projects: the threshold, with
    <em>Quando sono qui, non sono là</em>; the body's relationship to water, in the lineage of
    <em>En corps à la mer</em>; and, with <em>Is this love that I'm feeling?</em>, love as a
    possible place to give birth to oneself anew.</p>

    <p class="bio-inspirations">Inspirations: Claudia Andujar, Graciela Iturbide, Luigi Ghirri,
    Jacques-Henri Lartigue, Manuel Álvarez Bravo, Miguel Rio Branco, José Diniz, Letizia
    Battaglia, among others.</p>

  </div>

</Layout>
